<pre>Hi Heather,

I have exchanged a few emails with LBell, and sometimes being on the search
for Ushahidi talent I understand where the frustration comes from. 
Don't get me wrong, but directing someone that is not a coder to Github is
not a solution, nor is saying &quot;you need a feature, hack it yourself!&quot;, which
I've heard before - very cool, yes, but unenforceable for the average user
or for someone that has the intent, but does not have the time to
modify/adapt/fix the code.

The forums and Skype chat are fine, but they are not dependable. Sometimes
you will be lucky and get Linda, Emmanuel, Dale, Brian, David, or any other
&quot;top&quot; developer to reply at one particular issue - and they're always
spot-on - but many times you are left with the crickets :)

Ushahidi is getting bigger, and it is still moving fast, making very hard
for someone to be up-to-date, and maintain a stable operation at the same
time. Maybe this has not been realized yet, but when one says &quot;let's use
Ushahidi&quot; in a given project, particularly a larger one, that person is
making a bet. Not having a dependable support will make people think twice.

I think you know where I'm going with this; we are at the point where we
need to think of either creating (or formalizing) a support channel that
people like LBell can tap into, and start thinking of training. The former
has been a need for a while, and with proper curation will improve
Ushahidi's standing, and develop a revenue channel (yes, I'm talking about
*paid* support), for the latter, this could be a great time to do so,
considering the media interest in non-traditional training. 

Maybe we can discuss this some more and exchange a few ideas?

Best wishes,

Pablo Dest√©fanis


